# Active Directory Environment Build

## Purpose

Build a small Windows enterprise environment for practicing identity management, endpoint support, networking, troubleshooting, and security administration.

## Systems

| System | Operating System | Role |
|---|---|---|
| Domain Controller | Windows Server 2019 | Active Directory, DNS, DHCP, and authentication |
| CLIENT1 | Windows 10 | Domain-joined workstation |
| MBR-SRV01 | Windows Server 2022 | Domain-joined member server |

## Network

- Hypervisor: VMware Workstation
- Internal network: VMware LAN Segment
- Internal subnet: 172.16.0.0/24
- Domain controller provides DNS and DHCP
- CLIENT1 and MBR-SRV01 receive network configuration through DHCP

## Work Completed

- Created Windows Server virtual machines in VMware Workstation
- Installed Windows Server 2019 and Windows Server 2022
- Installed Active Directory Domain Services
- Created a new Active Directory forest and domain
- Configured DNS and DHCP
- Created domain users
- Joined CLIENT1 to the domain
- Joined MBR-SRV01 to the domain
- Confirmed both computer accounts in Active Directory Users and Computers
- Verified that the systems received valid IP addresses, gateway, and DNS information

## Why This Matters

Active Directory provides centralized management of users, computers, authentication, groups, permissions, and security settings.

A domain join creates a computer identity in Active Directory and establishes a trust relationship between the computer and the domain.

DNS allows domain members to locate the domain controller and other Active Directory services.

DHCP automatically supplies computers with an IP address, subnet mask, gateway, and DNS settings.

## Verification

The environment was verified by:

- Viewing CLIENT1 and MBR-SRV01 in Active Directory Users and Computers
- Running `ipconfig /all`
- Signing in with domain credentials
- Confirming the domain name in Windows Server Manager
- Confirming communication with the domain controller
